body:
The idea was to create a RESTful CMS API that would be edited using a client side app. On the backend, we use [flatiron](http://flatironjs.org/) and on the frontend [Chaplin](http://chaplinjs.org/) that itself wraps [Backbone](http://backbonejs.org/).

One defines a form associated with a page "type". This type is then modified in a presenter component and finally injected into an [eco](https://github.com/sstephenson/eco) template. The CMS then adds helper methods for accessing children, parent or sibling nodes in the presenter.

Authorization is done through [Mozilla Persona](http://www.mozilla.org/en-US/persona/) so one adds users with backend access priviledges simply by adding an email address.

Currently in use by University of Cambridge and this site.
description: A forms based node.js CMS ala SilverStripe
title: bla

body:
A reference implementation of a service with a client that makes it easy to embed widgets built using e.g. [Backbone.js](http://backbonejs.org/) on a page.

The service packages up CoffeeScript, eco and Stylus/CSS code into one JavaScript file that can be embedded on any page after satisfying its library requirements.

The hope is that people will move away from using jQuery and spaghetti code and embrace a light builder that is framework-agnostic.
title: InterMine Report Widgets

body:
A [Chaplin](http://chaplinjs.org/) powered app serving as a prototype of a workflow based system for InterMine data warehouse.

The app consists of "tools" that make themselves available when certain conditions are met, e.g.: "I have a list" which makes tools that export data available etc.

It creates "fake" URLs for everything using *pushState* so users feel like they are using a classical page-based app.

A cool addition is the ability to open links in new tabs and work with multiple tabs open. All tabs are synced through *LocalStorage* on a 1s schedule.

All tool steps executed are saved into a visual history.
description: Workflow based data mining UI using pushState and LocalHistory
title: InterMine Steps

**June 2012**

The reason behind this library was to improve on Google Visualization charts. As soon as you want to precisely position series/bar labels, you are stuck.

At the same time, [D3.js](http://d3js.org/) is not a charting library and is bloated.

This library offers precise chart rendering in SVG which calculates the dimensions of elements after they are rendered to move them around. At the same time one can also use CSS to theme the visualizations.

Lack of IE support (VML) is a problem but VML language is limited (no wrapping "g" elements).
description: Precise bar and column charts in SVG/JavaScript

The goal of this project is to develop a good enough parser/compiler for the logic programming language Prolog.

For parsing it uses a [PEG.js](http://pegjs.majda.cz/) grammar to make it easy for anyone to pass tokens straight up instead of providing a "text" input.

I am hoping this app will relaunch an interest in Language User Interfaces making database searches a little bit smarter.

The app reads a comma separated file and an associated CoffeeScript script executing the latter on the former. Access to sheet cells is done by exposing array variables like A, B etc. All is done quite efficiently by tokenizing the source and seeing which columns are going to be used.

The source code is then syntax highlighted.

The sheet UI behaves similar to that of Google Drive thanks to the [jQWidgets](http://www.jqwidgets.com) library.

body:
This project glues [haibu](https://github.com/nodejitsu/haibu) and [node-http-proxy](https://github.com/nodejitsu/node-http-proxy).

At the beginning the aim was to get our own PaaS cloud working on the open source [Nodejitsu](https://www.nodejitsu.com/). However, the offering was limited and I had to write more and more code to get the open source libraries to a usable state.

It has these improvements:

1. API token based authentication
1. Promiseful client and server components
1. Rewrite of routes and the backend to make it more secure and less glitchy
1. Private environment variables can now be POSTed without saving them with the app source code
1. A deployment client similar to the one used with other paid PaaS services

It is successfully being used by our team at University of Cambridge.
title: ukraine
